                    <head>
                        <title>Ólafs saga helga</title>
                        <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace>
                        <origDate notBefore="1390" notAfter="1410" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">c. 1400</origDate>
                        <note>The leaf is all that remains of a manuscript called <title type="ms">Codex Resenianus</title>. Peder Resen (d. 1688) was a man that
                            collected a number of manuscripts given to the university library of
                            Copenhagen. A catalogue of the collection was made: <bibl>
                                <title level="m">Petri Johannis Resenii bibliotheca regi academiæ
                                    Hafniensi donata</title>
                                <pubPlace>Hafniæ</pubPlace>
                                <date>M. DC. L. XXXV</date>
                            </bibl>, and the manuscript, now called Codex Resenianus, was then
                            described on p. 259 among the foliants as <q xml:lang="la">Capsa VIII.
                                Ord. I fol., nr 27</q>. Peder Resen's collection, however, together
                            with all of the university library, was destroyed in the great
                            Copenhagen fire of <date>1728</date>. On an AM-slip <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> wrote that the leaf once
                            belonged to a 7th gathering, that at his time was missing, and that the
                            rest of this gathering was all gone. He added that this lacuna was an
                            old one, what could be seen from an curse written in the manuscript upon
                            the one who stole the gathering. Before the Copenhagen fire Codex
                            Resenianus was copied for <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni
                                Magnússon</name>, and the content of the manuscript can now be found
                            in AM 78 a fol and AM 78 b fol.</note>
                    </head>
